post_text:
NSD students at 10 elementary schools will receive free, fresh fruit and vegetables this school year thanks to a state-administrated grant from the U.S. Department of Agriculture. The Fresh Fruit and Vegetable Program (FFVP) provides children with a variety of fruits and vegetables during the school day. Under the National School Lunch Act, schools with the highest enrollment of students identified for free and reduced-cost meals are given priority for participation.

Schools participating this year include Centennial, Central, Endeavor, Greenhurst, Iowa, New Horizons, Park Ridge, Sherman, Snake River and Willow Creek.

post_text: A huge shout out to the Nampa Association of Realtors for heading up this shoe drive that will bless so many lives!
shared_text:
Julie Skogsberg is with Mari Ramos.
August 21 at 2:00 PM ·

Shoe Drive 2020 We had a great time dropping off all of the shoes and supplies we collected for the Shoe Drive. The total amount of shoes we were able to give to the Nampa School District came out to... 351! 🎉 Our best year yet! Thank you to everyone at the Nampa Association of Realtors who continue to support us each year. And a BIG thank you to each and every one of you who donated shoes, socks, tissues, dish soap, laundry soap, ziploc bags and even some snacks. You are truly making a difference in our community especially in these unprecedented times. We are humbled by your generosity and can't wait until next year!
#shoedrive2020 #Shoesforkids #nampaassociationofrealtors #Nampaproud #communityfirst #namparealestateagents

post_text:
Starting Monday, August 24, Nampa School District will begin serving grab-and-go lunches; breakfast for the following day will also be available. Each meal will be charged according to the student’s Free, Reduced or Paid status (except for Central and Sherman students, who have Community Eligibility Provision status). Students will not be allowed to carry account balances greater than $50.

During online-only classes, we have developed a K-12 menu so that any student can pick up a meal at any school. Lunch will be served from 11:15 a.m. to noon at middle schools and high schools and from 11:15 a.m. to 12:15 p.m. at elementary schools.

Families should fill out the free and reduced priced meal application found at https://nampa.school/NLSPapp.

Breakfast
Students: No Charge
NOVA Student/Adult/Guest Child $2.75

Lunch
Paid Status $2.45 (Grades K-5)
Paid Status $2.70 (Grades 6-12)
Reduced Status $ .40
CEP (Central and Sherman) elementary schools – No Charge
NOVA Student/Adult/Guest Child $4.00

post_text:
Are you ready for back to school? Parents and guardians are an essential part of the education process, but it takes some work to support kids in online schooling. First, it’s important to develop and maintain a supportive academic home environment.

● Work with your school to secure appropriate devices and connectivity (internet) to support student learning at home
● Provide a consistent learning space for students
● Limit distractions during “school time”
● Create and follow a schedule to support student learning
● Organize learning spaces to maximize student learning
● Work with your school to access available resources

Find a list of resources, including broadband providers and regional community access points, at https://4.files.edl.io/56e5/08/14/20/161725-d2ba79a4-6e00-4ee7-97c5-810728037914.pdf

Nampa School District trustees voted on July 30 to delay the start of school for one week to allow teachers time to prepare to use a variety of teaching platforms. The first day of class will be Aug. 24.

Following reports from officials at St. Alphonsus, St. Luke’s and Southwest District Health, trustees also approved a plan to start school wholly online for at least the first two weeks, until after Labor Day. Canyon County currently is seeing a large spike in the percentage of positive COVID test results as well as high hospital occupancy rates. Current data puts the county in Southwest District Health’s Red category.

Idaho State Department of Education
July 14 at 6:00 PM ·

It's Operation Safe Driver Week! Remind young drivers and student drivers to minimize distractions and stay safe on the road! Also, remind young drivers of the three key safety challenges that large trucks and buses face:

1. Longer Stopping Distances

Trucks and buses need more stopping time and distance than smaller vehicles, and stopping distance increases with heavier loads or challenging road conditions.

2. Huge Blind Spots

Commercial motor vehicles have large blind spots around all four sides, so it’s important to take extra care when passing or being passed by large trucks and buses.

3. Wider Turning Radius

Trucks and buses don’t maneuver like cars and we need to give them extra space to turn.

Learn more via Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration: https://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/mission/about-us

post_text:
Meet the staff of NOVA, Nampa’s first virtual school opening this fall. Today we introduce you to Angela Luque, Secondary Science Teacher. Learn more, including how to register, at https://bit.ly/3ezOqa1

During her 17 years in education, Ms. Luque has served in a variety of roles: K-12 teacher, ISAT coordinator for the state of Idaho, substitute principal and college professor.
She earned a Bachelor of Science degree in biology from Boise State University, a master’s in teacher education with an emphasis in secondary education from Eastern Oregon University, an educational specialist degree from Northwest Nazarene University, and a doctorate in educational leadership from University of Phoenix.

Some fun facts about Ms. Luque:
• She enjoys camping, fishing, white water rafting, and hiking.
• She is married to a wonderful man and has two children. Her oldest is 19 and her youngest is 17.
• She has two dogs and a HUGE tortoise.
• She plays seven instruments.
• She loves spending time with her family and friends, enjoying the beautiful state that we live in!

‪Edit: If you know housebound seniors, anyone can get groceries for them too by driving through.‬

shared_text:
Idaho State Department of Education
June 22 at 3:42 PM ·

Superintendent Sherri Ybarra invites parents to join the virtual event, Idaho Ready to Learn: Countdown to Kindergarten, happening June 23 and 24 via Facebook live! Idaho Ready to Learn is an exciting new program that supports parents of incoming kindergarten students. This program will kick off with a live, 2-day statewide event via the Idaho PTV Families Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/events/592325604822085/. During this event, professionals around the state (including Supt. Ybarra and the director of our Special Education department, Charlie Silva) will share important information, tips, tricks, and activities to help parents get their children excited for kindergarten. Topics will include academic, social, and motor skills, how to access public libraries, and more. The event will begin streaming at 10:30 each day.

Find more information about Idaho Ready to Learn and a weekly schedule of fun, educational activities for incoming kindergartners at www.idahoptv.org/ReadyToLearn.

Idaho PTV Teachers
May 26 at 8:00 AM ·

Teaching 6th grade ELA this week for #ClassroomIdaho on Idaho Public Television is the wonderful Susie Finney from Central Elementary in the Nampa School District. Be sure to watch her on our Create channel or on YouTube.

Susie Finney is a 5th grade teacher at Central Elementary in Nampa, Idaho. She graduated from Boise State with an Elementary Education degree in 2018. Susie is in her second year teaching, but first year in 5th grade. She is passionate about her work and strives to make every student feel their true potential. She spends her free time hiking and backpacking in the Idaho wilderness with her husband and two big dogs.

Census data supports our schools and is mandated by the U.S. Constitution. The census is a once-every-decade count of everyone living in the country. When we know how many people live in your community, organizations, and businesses are better
equipped to evaluate the services and programs needed, such as clinics, schools, and roads. It also determines how seats in Congress are distributed among the 50 states. Stu Hobson
June 3 at 6:04 PM ·

Selfie with Stu

Meet Riley Brown, Nampa High 2016 Graduate. He was part of the last Class for me as the NHS SRO. Riley played basketball and baseball for the Bulldogs. Though he was not one of my DARE students I remember umpiring his games from Little League.

Riley just graduated from Boise State last month and this week started as the new Program Director at the Nampa Boys and Girls Club. He also coaches Basketball at Columbia High School with one of my other former NHS students Trevor Morris.

It was great to see Riley today and to know we will be work neighbors.

Keep up the good work Riley. Another example of a NHS Bulldog doing great things in our community.

PS. Notice the social distancing Selfie

post_text: Free suicide prevention training for anyone who interacts with students at school or at home.
shared_text:
Idaho State Department of Education
May 29 at 9:41 AM ·

The Idaho State Department of Education is offering free online QPR (Question, Persuade and Refer) Gatekeeper Training for Suicide Prevention. This training is available to educators and any member of a school's community (this includes parents, grandparents, school staff, staff at youth organizations, coaches; anyone who interacts with students at home or at school).

The training takes about 1-2 hours to complete. Apply here: https://form.jotform.com/200843987115156

We want as many caring adults as possible prepared and trained to connect students with support and resources! Thank you for taking the time to complete this course which will help you protect and support our youth.

post_text: Look! It's our very own Kiersten Rood from Endeavor!
shared_text:
Idaho PTV Teachers
May 27 at 7:30 AM ·

This week, third graders across Idaho get to learn from the one and only Kiersten Rood from Endeavor Elementary in the Nampa School District during #ClassroomIdaho on Idaho Public Television! Be sure to tune in during the final week, or catch it on YouTube.

Kiersten Rood is a 4th grade teacher at Endeavor Elementary School in Nampa, Idaho. She graduated from Utah State University in Elementary Education with an English as a Second Language Endorsement. She taught 3rd grade in Las Vegas, Nevada for two years before moving to Boise, Idaho and joining the Endeavor team. She has since taught 3rd, 4th, and 5th grade. Her favorite things to do outside of teaching are playing video games, going for walks, baking bread, and gardening.

https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLvDo4LDXnoaCLuIIer_edEGRT6M8itOWD

Public Works Week celebrated the men and women in our community who serve the City of Nampa. If you missed them on our Create channel, you can watch them on our YouTube channel, linked below!

Taylor Warren is a 4th Grade teacher at Endeavor Elementary in Nampa, Idaho. During her free time, Taylor enjoys being outside, spending quality time with friends and exercising.

post_text: This Saturday, May 16, at 7 p.m. Mountain Time, former President Barack Obama will deliver a commencement address to graduating seniors nationwide as part of an hour-long multimedia Graduate Together: America Honors the High School Class of 2020 event. This program will be aired simultaneously Saturday evening by more than 20 broadcast TV and digital streaming partners. Joining Obama will be NBA star and school founder LeBron James, Nobel Prize winner Malala Yousafzai, the Jonas Brothers and soccer superstar Megan Rapinoe, among others. The event will feature highlights from thousands of student submissions, a collection of commencement addresses, celebrity performances and inspirational vignettes. Learn more about this event.

post_text:
Congratulations to the following graduating Nampa High seniors for earning Bridge Scholars Awards from Northwest Nazarene University.

Enoch Bautista
Ashley Christine Bradbeer
Brian James Johannsen
Sophia Bevry Long
Chandler Belle Prindle
Elisa Ann Reece
Hanna Grace Seabaugh

These seniors earned this award by taking 15 or more credits though the NNU Concurrent Credit Program AND maintaining a 3.5 or better in these college level courses.

Next week, they will receive in the mail, an NNU Bridge Scholar medallion and a letter of congratulations that also offers them an additional $1,000 yearly scholarship to attend NNU.

post_text: Aw thanks! We love feeding these kiddos!
shared_text:
Maggie O'Mara
April 24 at 10:00 AM ·

“We had to go by the school to get my daughter’s things, and they were handing out lunches. The girls were thrilled, and that is a lot of food! I’m beyond impressed. I thanked them for all that they are doing. I can’t express how they have gone above and beyond for our kids. Thank you!” - Cortney Schuetz

This grateful mom wanted to express her appreciation for the lunch staff at Ronald Reagan Elementary in Nampa. Kids 1-18 years of age are able to get lunches daily. They even put breakfast in for the following day.

We want to honor all the people making grab & go meals for the kids in the Treasure Valley. You are heroes!

#GoodNews

post_text: A HUGE thank you to Rep. Rick Youngblood, who joined the Blue Cross of Idaho Foundation’s Steps for Schools challenge to benefit the Nampa School District! Youngblood’s $750 donation will promote physical activity among students through the purchase of equipment or in support of walking programs.

Great news! The Nampa FFA Greenhouse Plant Sale is back this Friday and Saturday, April 24-25. To comply with social distancing, you will need to sign up for a specific “shopping time slot.” Friends and family must have their own assigned time in order to accompany you.

Hanging baskets are $20, patio pots are $18, most 6-inch pots are $4, most 6-packs will be $2, and veggies are 50 cents per plant

The greenhouse is on the west/back side of Columbia High School and can be accessed via Amity Road. Pay with card, check or EXACT cash. No change can be given.

Sign up now at: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/10C0C4EADA923A6FA7-nampa

post_text: Yeah - we got this!

April 8 at 10:54 PM ·

It truly is a partnership. Our families are working hard to keep kids engaged in the learning opportunities our teachers thoughtfully and lovingly create for them. Dining tables become classrooms. Teachers’ homes become virtual learning centers. We keep our distance physically to stop the spread of the virus. We become closer mentally and emotionally so that all children can access learning.
As a principal, I am in awe of the efforts and results of ALL parties involved. We are proud to be Mustangs! #nsdcourage We’ve GOT this!

post_text: Great work is still happening! Good job Reagan!
shared_text:
Ronald Reagan Elementary School
March 27 at 12:14 PM ·

Reagan third graders woke up to some great news. After working hard to raise money to build wells and send kids to school in Cambodia, they learned that the first well has already been installed and is ready to use!

Even with cutting the Water for a Well fundraiser short, our third graders raised enough money to build TWO wells and pay for an annual tuition fee for a local village child.

The Khatt family's daily income is $1-$2. Before CCDO provided the family their own water well, they used to get water from their neighbors well. To fetch the water, they had to walk between 10-20 minutes.

It puts our current struggles into perspective. We are so proud of these kids, their hearts, their ability to empathize, and their desire to serve!
#ReaganWay 💚

post_text:
The Governor, in collaboration with the Idaho Association of School Administrators, the Idaho School Board Association and the State Superintendent’s office, has scheduled a conference call for today, March 15, to address COVID-19 with education stakeholders. The Governor's Office has requested that we wait until after this conference call to make any decisions related to school closure. Parents, please watch for an email later tonight.

As we consider next steps, it is important to remember that our neighborhood schools are centers for our community and provide meals and other critical services for our students. Students receive the best educational experience when in school. As long as our schools remain safe for students, staff and our community, we will remain open. If school closures are required, we will do our best to provide parents and staff with as much notice as possible.

In light of the heightened awareness of the COVID-19 outbreak, we feel it is in the best interest of our students, staff, and families to suspend all district-sponsored out-of-state travel through April 30th. This includes all athletics, activities, conferences, professional development, and any other district-related event that requires out-of-state travel.

We understand the difficulty this may cause but want to keep the health and safety of our school community foremost in our thinking. We will continue to assess the situation as new information becomes available and will work to keep those in our school district informed.

post_text:
After placing second in the Idaho State robotics competition and first in the Middle School Excellence Awards, East Valley’s robotics team is now headed to the Vex Robotics World Championship. The competition is April 21-26 in Louisville, Kentucky.

The trip will cost about $7,500-$8,000 for coach Jesus Gomez and his four-girl team. To help with costs, the team is holding two Great Harvest Bread Company fundraisers. The first is March 6-17, with the delivery of bread to East Valley on March 19. The second is March 18-April 1, with delivery to East Valley on April 3. Options are Cinnamon Burst and/or Pumpkin Chocolate Chip bread.

You can pay with cash, checks or credit cards in the front office at East Valley, located at 4085 E. Greenhurst Rd., or online at www.EastValleyStore.com.

post_text: Six steps to prevent the spread of respiratory diseases.
shared_text:
Nampa Idaho Fire Department
March 4 at 11:54 AM ·

Help prevent the spread of respiratory disease like Coronavirus Disease with these simple 6 steps:
1. Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
2. Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash.
3. Avoid touching your eyes,nose, and mouth.
4. Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.
5. Stay home when you are sick, except to get medical care.
6. Wash your hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.

Nampa Police Department City of Nampa, Idaho - Municipal Government #TakeCareandBeSafe
